title: The Natural Mother of the Child: A Memoir of Nonbinary Parenthood
author: Belc, Krys Malcolm*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: This is going to be one of those memoirs that I'm glad to own and that I can see myself recommending to a lot of people. Consider this my recommendatiThis is going to be one of those memoirs that I'm glad to own and that I can see myself recommending to a lot of people. Consider this my recommendation to you: read this memoir.First, the form is innovative-- snack sized sections, with different audiences (the "you" addressed throughout shifts), set off with images and text from legal documents.Second, there is such raw power in the prose here. The descriptions of pregnancy, love, parenting and being parented are so apt that I had to slow down while reading. Third, there is no easy black and white here, although all of the pictures are that way. Bodies are messy, marriages and families are messy, and the way that people perceive gestational mothers who don't present as female: definitely messy. I had never really thought about all of the inherent language that could isolate nonbinary pregnant and nursing people before, but I will now. Get it for yourself, and/or request for your local library. ...more

title: Dawg Towne: a Novel
author: Kaltman, Alice*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: A completely original braided-narrative novel. Over the course of a year in Towne, dogs will get lost and found, and relationships will change foreverA completely original braided-narrative novel. Over the course of a year in Towne, dogs will get lost and found, and relationships will change forever. Kaltman's book brings us into six different threads and households to see these transformations take place: a loner girl, a teen questioning their sexuality, an interior designer searching for something bigger, a widower, a washed-up actor aching to be a better man, and a new father novelist who can't write. As is normal with this kind of multiple POV book, I did favor some perspectives and find myself leaning away from others, but they all moved the book forward in necessary ways. The most compelling perspectives for me were the new father and loner teen, and I'm sure that other voices will speak most to other people. DAWG TOWNE speaks to what community can build and what it can break down. A really interesting new novel....more

title: How Beautiful We Were
author: Mbue, Imbolo*
my rating: 1 of 5 stars2 of 5 stars3 of 5 stars4 of 5 stars5 of 5 starsadd to shelves
review: This novel is a woven story, told from the perspective of many points of view, all centered around a fictional African village. The village, taken oveThis novel is a woven story, told from the perspective of many points of view, all centered around a fictional African village. The village, taken over in every practical sense by an oil company, struggles to regain its ancestral land and keep its children from dying from the poisonous water. Over the course of the novel, Mbue takes the reader on a journey not just through one generation, but many, as the aftereffects of this environmental and capitalist overreach wreak havoc. The story mainly centers on a girl named Thula, who holds the hopes and fears of all of the village with her. I was immediately grabbed by this novel, its first grounding perspective told in a first person plural, "we, the children" as they watch a horrific event. From there, I couldn't put this novel down and resented each time I had to. Passionate, lush prose. While there were many tertiary characters that could sometimes be harder to track, in its fullness, this novel is devastating and, indeed, beautiful. Glad to have read it.Thank you to LibroFM for the audio advanced copy-- a full cast production (the best kind of audiobook!)...more
